{"title_page": "1954 British Virgin Islands general election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Politics of the British Virgin Islands}}\n\nThe '''British Virgin Islands general election, 1954''' was a general election held in the [[British Virgin Islands]] in 1954 for seats on the [[Legislative Council of the British Virgin Islands]].  The exact date of the election is not recorded, although based on contemporary records it appears to have been in April.<ref>Edwin Leonard was elected in the 3rd District, but it is recorded that his term only lasted from April 1954 to August 1954 ({{cite web |url=http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |title=BVI election and information results 1950-2011 |publisher=BVI Deputy Governor's Office |page=65 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}).</ref>  Similarly the exact vote tallies in each of the districts is not recorded, nor are the names of the candidates who stood.\n\nThe [[British Virgin Islands general election, 1950|previous election in 1950]] had elected four members to the Council on the basis of a Territory-wide vote.  The 1954 election was the first election to employ districting.  The Territory was divided into five districts, the largest of which (the 2nd District - [[Road Town]]) would have two members.  All seats were contested.\n\n==Results==\nAt the time candidates were not affiliated with [[political parties]].  Notable candidates who were elected for the first time included Theodolph Faulkner, remembered for [[British_Virgin_Islands_general_election,_1950#Background|his key role]] in relation to the reintroduction of democracy in the British Virgin Islands.\n\nExact voting counts are not recorded, but the following candidates were declared winners:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |title=BVI election and information results 1950-2011 |publisher=BVI Deputy Governor's Office |page=65 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''List of Elected Members'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"200\"|District \n! width=\"200\"|Member(s)\n|-\n| 1st District\n|Wilfred W. Smith\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2nd District<br />(two members)\n|[[Howard Reynold Penn|H.R. Penn]], [[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]]\n|-\n|[[Isaac Glanville Fonseca|Isaac G. Fonseca]]\n|-\n|3rd District\n|Edwin H. Leonard\n|-\n|4th District\n|Leslie Franklyn Malone\n|-\n|5th District\n|Theodolph Faulkner\n|}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf BVI election and information results 1950-2011]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{British Virgin Islands elections}}\n\n[[Category:Elections in the British Virgin Islands|1954]]\n[[Category:1954 elections in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:1954 in the British Virgin Islands|General election]]\n\n\n{{BritishVirginIslands-stub}}\n{{caribbean-election-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Politics of the British Virgin Islands}}\n\nThe '''British Virgin Islands general election, 1954''' was a general election held in the [[British Virgin Islands]] in 1954 for seats on the [[Legislative Council of the British Virgin Islands]].  The exact date of the election is not recorded, although based on contemporary records it appears to have been in April.<ref>Edwin Leonard was elected in the 3rd District, but it is recorded that his term only lasted from April 1954 to August 1954 ({{cite web |url=http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |title=BVI election and information results 1950-2011 |publisher=BVI Deputy Governor's Office |page=65 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}).</ref>  Similarly the exact vote tallies in each of the districts is not recorded, nor are the names of the candidates who stood.\n\nThe [[British Virgin Islands general election, 1950|previous election in 1950]] had elected four members to the Council on the basis of a Territory-wide vote.  The 1954 election was the first election to employ districting.  The Territory was divided into five districts, the largest of which (the 2nd District - [[Road Town]]) would have two members.  All seats were contested.\n\n==Results==\nAt the time candidates were not affiliated with [[political parties]].  Notable candidates who were elected for the first time included Theodolph Faulkner, remembered for [[British_Virgin_Islands_general_election,_1950#Background|his key role]] in relation to the reintroduction of democracy in the British Virgin Islands.\n\nExact voting counts are not recorded, but the following candidates were declared winners:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |title=BVI election and information results 1950-2011 |publisher=BVI Deputy Governor's Office |page=65 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''List of Elected Members'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"200\"|District \n! width=\"200\"|Member(s)\n|-\n| 1st District\n|Wilfred W. Smith\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2nd District<br />(two members)\n|[[